# Task Completion Notification

After completing any user-requested task, send a push notification to the user's phone via ntfy.

## When to notify

- After finishing implementation, fix, debug, refactor, or any concrete work the user asked for
- After committing code (if a commit was part of the task)
- After completing a plan, research document, or review

## When NOT to notify

- After asking a clarifying question (nothing was completed)
- After only providing information or answering a question
- Mid-task when pausing for user input or approval
- If the task failed and you're reporting the failure

## How to notify

Run this shell command as the **very last action** of your turn:

```sh
curl -s -o /dev/null ntfy.sh/david-toolkit-notify -d "Task finished: <one sentence summary>"
```

Replace `<one sentence summary>` with a concise, specific description of what was done.

### Examples

```sh
curl -s -o /dev/null ntfy.sh/david-toolkit-notify -d "Task finished: Added CSV export validation with error handling for malformed rows"
curl -s -o /dev/null ntfy.sh/david-toolkit-notify -d "Task finished: Fixed mobile layout overflow on dashboard cards"
curl -s -o /dev/null ntfy.sh/david-toolkit-notify -d "Task finished: Created implementation plan for inventory tracking feature"
```

## Rules

- ONE sentence, max ~15 words — enough to know what happened, not a changelog
- Be specific about what was done, not generic ("Fixed the bug" is bad; "Fixed decimal comma parsing in CSV importer" is good)
- Do NOT include file paths, stack traces, or technical jargon
- This is the LAST thing you do — after all verification, commits, and cleanup
- Do NOT wait for confirmation to send the notification — just send it
